[[ru:Цикл просмотра]]

'''Inguma''' (or '''Mauma''', as called in [[Baigorri]]), was the [[god]] of dreams in [[Basque mythology]] and religion.<ref>Theresa Bane, ''Encyclopedia of Beasts and Monsters in Myth, Legend and Folklore'', 2016</ref> He was regarded as a malevolent force who entered houses at night and plagued the residents with [[nightmare]]s. He also kills people while sleeping.
==References== <references /> * Theresa Bane, ''Encyclopedia of Beasts and Monsters in Myth, Legend and Folklore'', 2016
[[Category:Basque gods]] [[Category:Dream]] [[Category:Sleep in mythology and folklore]] {{BasqueCountry-stub}} {{Europe-myth-stub}}

{{Orphan|date=February 2015}}
{{Infobox person | name = Katharine McCook Knox | image = File:Katherine McCook Knox HCFFPA001440f.jpg | image_size = | alt = Katherine McCook Knox | caption = | birth_date = 1889 | birth_place = [[Washington, D.C.]] | death_date = {{Death date|1983|07|09}} | death_place = | residence = | nationality = | alma_mater = | occupation = Art historian | organization = | known_for = | notable_works = * The Story of the Frick Art Reference Library : The Early Years * The Sharples: Their Portraits of George Washington and his Contemporaries | style = | home_town = }}
'''Katharine McCook Knox''' was an American art historian, best known for her history of the [[Frick Art Reference Library]], and for curatorial work on presidential portraits.
== Personal Life == Katharine McCook was born in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 1889 and was raised in New York City. Her parents were Anson George McCook, a Civil War general and Secretary of the Senate from New York, and Hettie Beatty.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=http://cornell.worldcat.org/oclc/5196423|title=The story of the Frick Art Reference Library: the early years|last=Knox|first=Katharine McCook|last2=Frick Art Reference Library|date=1979|publisher=The Library|year=|isbn=|location=New York|pages=147-149|language=English}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> In 1911, she married Hugh Smith Knox, the son of Senator [[Philander C. Knox|Philander Chase Knox]], but divorced in 1916.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Divorces Hugh Knox|last=Special to the Washington Post|first=|date=Feb 3, 1916|work=The Washington Post|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|page=2}}</ref> She had one daughter, Kathleen Knox Smith.<ref>"Knox, Katharine McCook" Ancestry.com. ''U.S., Social Security Applications and Claims Index, 1936-2007'' [database on-line]. Provo, UT, USA: Ancestry.com Operations, Inc., 2015.</ref>
== Career == Knox is known for her history of the [[Frick Art Reference Library]], and for her work on presidential portraits, particularly on [[George Washington]] and [[Abraham Lincoln]]. Early in her career, she catalogued works of art in the [[White House]] art collection during the [[Herbert Hoover]] administration.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Sloan's Auction Set|last=Conroy|first=Sarah Booth|date=28 Jan 1984|work=The Washington Post|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|page=B8}}</ref> She also served as consultant for exhibitions at the [[Smithsonian Institution]], the [[The Phillips Collection|Phillips Collection]], the [[Textile Museum (Washington, D.C.)|Textile Museum]], the [[Daughters of the American Revolution|National Society Daughters of the American Revolution Museum]], and the [[Corcoran Gallery of Art]], all in Washington, D.C.<ref name=":1" /> She was awarded the Corcoran Gallery of Art's Medal of Merit in 1966.<ref name=":1" /> A member of the Washington D.C. Republican Central Committee and program chair of the League of Republican Women of the District of Columbia, she rediscovered a portrait by [[George Peter Alexander Healy|G. P. A. Healy]] of Abraham Lincoln, and convinced the [[United States Postal Service|U. S. Post Office]] to select it for a commemorative stamp during the Lincoln Sesquicentennial celebration in 1959.<ref name=":0" /> In honor of this discovery, the Lincoln Sesquicentennial Commission awarded Knox the Abraham Lincoln medallion in 1960.<ref name=":1" /> She served as consultant in 1963 for the book published by the [[United States Capitol Historical Society]] about the U.S. Capitol, ''We, the People.''<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://cornell.worldcat.org/oclc/711000|title=We, the people; the story of the United States Capitol, its past and its promise.|last=Aikman|first=Lonnelle|last2=United States Capitol Historical Society|last3=National Geographic Society (U.S.)|date=1963|publisher=United States Capitol Historical Society|location=Washington|language=English}}</ref><ref name=":1" /> Knox was a Trustee of the Frick Art Reference Library.<ref name=":1" />
Knox died in [[Washington, D.C.]] on July 10, 1983.<ref>Obituary 1 -- no title. (1983, Jul 15), p. B11. ''The Washington Post (1974-Current File)'' Retrieved from <nowiki>https://search.proquest.com/docview/147571243?accountid=10267</nowiki> </ref><ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=http://rs5.loc.gov/service/mss/eadxmlmss/eadpdfmss/2013/ms013100.pdf|title=Katharine McCook Knox papers|last1=|first1=|last2=|first2=|date=|website=|publisher=Library of Congress|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=25 November 2013}} </ref>
==Publications== * Knox, Katherine McCook. 1932. "Washington and his associates". American Magazine of Art. XXIV (6): 399-408. {{OCLC|34529111}} * ''Surprise Personalities in Georgetown, D.C.'' 1958.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/39448797|title=Surprise personalities in Georgetown, D.C.|last=Knox|first=Katharine McCook|date=1959|location=Washington?|language=English}}</ref> * ''The Story of the Frick Art Reference Library : The Early Years'' New York: The Library. 1979.<ref name=":1" /> * [http://arcade.nyarc.org/record=b264160~S6 ''The Sharples: Their Portraits of George Washington and his Contemporaries: A Diary and an Account of the Life and Work of James Sharples and his Family in England and America.''] New York Kennedy Graphics. 1972. {{OCLC|2339340}}
==External links== * Library of Congress [http://rs5.loc.gov/service/mss/eadxmlmss/eadpdfmss/2013/ms013100.pdf Katharine McCook Knox papers] * [https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/history/art/presart-3.html White House Archives]
