{{Single source|date=December 2018}} {{italic title}} '''''Play-Doh''''' is a painted aluminum sculpture by [[Jeff Koons]], made between 1994 and 2014. Five copies were made, each measuring approximately 120 × 108 × 108 in. (304.8 × 274.3 × 274.3 cm). It is formed of 27 separate pieces of polychromed aluminum and was first publicly shown at the retrospective of Koons' work in 1994 at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] in NYC.<ref>[https://whitney.org/Education/ForTeachers/TeacherGuides/JeffKoons Whitney Museum of American Art 2014 Teacher Guide/Jeff Koons]</ref> The title refers to the modeling compound named [[Play-Doh]] which is used for arts and crafts projects by young children.
While speaking in reference to the sculpture ''"Play-Doh",'' Koons has said that he tries to "make objects that you can't make any judgements about". In the same commentary Koons said "If you take Play-Doh apart...they're organic shapes that all stack on top of each other...so that these surfaces are meeting on the inside and you never see that...the public doesn't see it but I think that you feel it and it has kind of a Freudian quality to it. I really thought that Play-Doh captures the twentieth century and you have this aspect of Freud with this mound of Play-Doh and the way the organic shapes are on top of each other...and within art you have this [[abstract expressionism]]...you have this aspect of [[Willem de Kooning|DeKooning]] or something..."<ref>[https://whitney.org/WatchAndListen/154 Whitney Museum, Koons, Play-Doh sculpture]</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
==External links== * [https://www.artdependence.com/articles/jeff-koons-monumental-play-doh-sculpture/ artdependence 2018 Koons, Play-Doh sculpture] * [https://news.artnet.com/market/christies-jeff-koons-play-doh-1258166 artnet 2018 Koons, Play-Doh sculpture] * [https://www.christies.com/features/Play-Doh-by-Jeff-Koons-9143-3.aspx christies Koons, Play-Doh sculpture] (good image) * [https://www.christies.com/features/Play-Doh-by-Jeff-Koons-9143-3.aspx christies.com] Koons discusses the sculpture, good images of the sculpture included
